# Java Type Design

## Eliminate Primitive Obsession
- Wrap domain concepts in value objects: `EmailAddress`, `Money`, `OrderId` instead of raw `String`/`long`
- Use records for simple value objects: `record EmailAddress(String value) {}`
- Add validation in compact constructors
- Provides type safety, self-documentation, and a natural home for behavior

## Type Hierarchies
- Model closed domains with sealed interfaces/classes
- Use interfaces for contracts, abstract classes only when sharing implementation
- Keep hierarchies shallow -- prefer composition
- Nested static classes for logical grouping within a type

## Strategic Type Selection
- `Optional` for method returns that may be empty -- never for fields or parameters
- `Set` when uniqueness matters, `List` when order matters
- Code to interfaces (`List`, `Map`, `Set`) not implementations (`ArrayList`, `HashMap`)
- `BigDecimal` for all financial/monetary calculations -- never `float`/`double`

## Fluent Interfaces
- Builder pattern for complex object construction with many optional parameters
- Return `this` for method chaining; return a new instance for immutable builders
- Validate in `build()` method, not in individual setters

## Consistent Naming
- Domain-driven names that match the ubiquitous language
- Aligned method signatures across related classes (same parameter order, similar return types)
- Interface/implementation: descriptive pairs (`PaymentGateway` / `StripePaymentGateway`)

## Generics for Reusability
- Use generic type parameters for reusable containers and algorithms
- Bounded type parameters for constraints: `<T extends Comparable<T>>`
- PECS: Producer Extends, Consumer Super

## Self-Documenting Types
- Types should be self-explanatory: `Duration timeout` not `long timeoutMs`
- Use enums for fixed sets of values with behavior
- Records for immutable data transfer

